247
00:07:40,414 --> 00:07:41,981
- How does you buying
one novelty cup

248
00:07:42,025 --> 00:07:43,243
help the company's stock price?

249
00:07:43,287 --> 00:07:44,679
- It boosts confidence
in the marketplace.

250
00:07:44,723 --> 00:07:46,507
You just don't know anything
about business, Terry!

251
00:07:46,551 --> 00:07:47,900
- Okay, so we've ruined
their outfits.

252
00:07:47,944 --> 00:07:49,684
Why will that
"reignite the passion"?

253
00:07:49,728 --> 00:07:51,034
- Because it will force them
to change

254
00:07:51,077 --> 00:07:53,166
into clothes which I will have
carefully placed

255
00:07:53,210 --> 00:07:54,689
at the top of their suitcases.

256
00:07:54,733 --> 00:07:57,736
Thus changing them both
into a couple of thirst traps.

257
00:07:57,780 --> 00:08:00,130
- Kevin Cozner, preparing to
descend the master stairca—

258
00:08:00,173 --> 00:08:04,569
- Oh, I see you've changed
into your... mock turtleneck.

259
00:08:04,612 --> 00:08:08,703
- And you into your...
exercise shorts.

260
00:08:08,747 --> 00:08:11,141
- I feel dirty.
You feel dirty?

261
00:08:11,184 --> 00:08:13,752
- I do.
And I love it.

262
00:08:13,796 --> 00:08:14,884
[baby crying]

263
00:08:14,927 --> 00:08:16,799
- Oh, hey, Amy.
Starting round three.

264
00:08:16,842 --> 00:08:19,062
You wanna try New Mexico-style
Chile Verde?

265
00:08:19,105 --> 00:08:21,151
- Uh, my hands are kind
of full here, Scully.

266
00:08:21,194 --> 00:08:23,370
- I can toss it to you.
- Wha—

267
00:08:23,414 --> 00:08:26,025
Scully, don't throw chips
at my baby!

268
00:08:26,069 --> 00:08:28,332
Gosh.
[sighs]

269
00:08:28,375 --> 00:08:30,987
Ugh.
Shh, shh, shh.

270
00:08:31,030 --> 00:08:33,728
[sighs] I can't believe
what I'm about to do.

271
00:08:33,772 --> 00:08:35,948
Charles, I need your help.
- I'm not gonna gloat.

272
00:08:35,992 --> 00:08:38,516
I'm just happy
he's getting the care he needs.

273
00:08:38,559 --> 00:08:40,561
- Okay, you might wanna be
a little less cocky

274
00:08:40,605 --> 00:08:41,911
until after you
actually get him down.

275
00:08:41,954 --> 00:08:43,738
Because, you know,
some babies are just fussy

276
00:08:43,782 --> 00:08:45,392
and there's nothing
that anyone can—

277
00:08:45,436 --> 00:08:46,916
oh, my God, is he asleep?

278
00:08:46,959 --> 00:08:48,874
- [whispering]
So can I be cocky now?

279
00:08:48,918 --> 00:08:51,442
- Step three:
a romantic picnic.

280
00:08:51,485 --> 00:08:53,444
The perfect gill net
for our trout to swim into.

281
00:08:53,487 --> 00:08:54,880
- Huh?
- Sorry.

282
00:08:54,924 --> 00:08:56,360
I've been watching that
survivalist show "Alone."

283
00:08:56,403 --> 00:08:57,578
It's really helped
with my metaphors.

284
00:08:57,622 --> 00:08:59,058
- You think they'll agree
to have a picnic?

285
00:08:59,102 --> 00:09:00,886
They won't even be
in the same room together.

286
00:09:00,930 --> 00:09:02,757
- It's not like we have
an unbaited gill net, Terry.

287
00:09:02,801 --> 00:09:04,585
What's your plan?
Forage for berries?

288
00:09:04,629 --> 00:09:06,892
[laughs] You wouldn't last
two days in the Arctic, man.

289
00:09:06,936 --> 00:09:08,198
- What are we doing now?

290
00:09:08,241 --> 00:09:09,329
- We're getting Holt and Kevin
back together!

291
00:09:09,373 --> 00:09:11,331
Now for Operation Corn Crake.

292
00:09:11,375 --> 00:09:12,724
Hey, Kevin, I have a question.

293
00:09:12,767 --> 00:09:14,769
- Is the corn crake
an important bird?

294
00:09:14,813 --> 00:09:15,858
- Yes.

295
00:09:15,901 --> 00:09:16,946
- They're among
the rarest species

296
00:09:16,989 --> 00:09:18,295
in the northeastern
United States.

297
00:09:18,338 --> 00:09:19,905
- A veritable holy grail

298
00:09:19,949 --> 00:09:21,428
within the bird watching
community.

299
00:09:21,472 --> 00:09:22,429
both: Oh, wow!

300
00:09:22,473 --> 00:09:23,474
- I only ask because...

301
00:09:23,517 --> 00:09:24,649
- I read that one was spotted

302
00:09:24,692 --> 00:09:25,998
in the woods near here.

303
00:09:26,042 --> 00:09:27,565
both: Grab your binoculars.
We're going birding.

304
00:09:27,608 --> 00:09:28,958
- Yeah, we are.

305
00:09:29,001 --> 00:09:30,916
- We're pretty far north
for a corn crake.

306
00:09:30,960 --> 00:09:32,483
Where did you hear
of this sighting?

307
00:09:32,526 --> 00:09:34,311
- Oh, on the birdwatching app

308
00:09:34,354 --> 00:09:36,356
that Captain Holt
recommended I download.

309
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:37,662
You know how he is
about birding.

310
00:09:37,705 --> 00:09:39,185
I guess you guys have that
in common, huh?

311
00:09:39,229 --> 00:09:41,579
- Hardly—Raymond is an
adequate birdwatcher at best.

312
00:09:41,622 --> 00:09:43,494
He once confused
a pileated woodpecker

313
00:09:43,537 --> 00:09:44,974
with a downy woodpecker.

314
00:09:45,017 --> 00:09:46,236
- Yeah.

315
00:09:46,279 --> 00:09:49,935
Pileated bootdecker
and a pileated jecker.

316
00:09:49,979 --> 00:09:51,371
- Huh.

317
00:09:51,415 --> 00:09:53,069
[sighs]
It's nowhere.

318
00:09:53,112 --> 00:09:55,114
- Uh, maybe you could flush out
the corn crake

319
00:09:55,158 --> 00:09:56,637
by doing its mating call?

320
00:09:56,681 --> 00:09:59,510
- I don't know why a corn crake
would make such a call

321
00:09:59,553 --> 00:10:01,468
three months
after its rooting season,

322
00:10:01,512 --> 00:10:05,124
but I suppose
it can't hurt to try.

323
00:10:05,168 --> 00:10:08,911
[imitates bird squawking]

324
00:10:09,824 --> 00:10:11,348
- Hold on.
That call.

325
00:10:11,391 --> 00:10:13,524
That's the call a corn crake
makes when it wants to root.

326
00:10:13,567 --> 00:10:16,309
I'll respond.
[clears throat]

327
00:10:16,353 --> 00:10:18,964
[imitates bird call]

328
00:10:19,008 --> 00:10:21,445
- [imitates bird call]

329
00:10:21,488 --> 00:10:23,273
- This way.

330
00:10:23,316 --> 00:10:25,840
[light music]

331
00:10:25,884 --> 00:10:28,147
- [whispering]
Oh, and do you need the shades?

332
00:10:28,191 --> 00:10:32,021
No, you don't,
'cause you're already asleep.

333
00:10:32,064 --> 00:10:35,415
- He forgot the sleep sack!
And Mac doesn't even care!

334
00:10:35,459 --> 00:10:36,764
I can't watch this.

335
00:10:36,808 --> 00:10:39,332
- [whispering]
Yes! Wow!

336
00:10:39,376 --> 00:10:42,292
[quirky music]

337
00:10:42,335 --> 00:10:45,643
♪

338
00:10:45,686 --> 00:10:47,950
Uh...
oh, no, no, no, no.

339
00:10:47,993 --> 00:10:49,038
Oh!

340
00:10:49,081 --> 00:10:50,822
I think I just locked
Mac in his room.

341
00:10:50,865 --> 00:10:52,693
What do I do?
- Oh, sorry, man.

342
00:10:52,737 --> 00:10:54,521
I think the second edible
just kicked in.

343
00:10:54,565 --> 00:10:55,870
This is a little too much
for me.

344
00:10:55,914 --> 00:10:57,785
Also, this is not the vibe
I was looking for.

345
00:10:57,829 --> 00:10:59,048
- No, no, no,
Ro-ro, Ro-ro.

346
00:10:59,091 --> 00:11:00,266
I need your help.

347
00:11:00,310 --> 00:11:02,051
- No, no, no.
Adios, amigo.

348
00:11:02,094 --> 00:11:03,922
- [huffs]

349
00:11:05,271 --> 00:11:11,321
- [imitates bird call]

350
00:11:11,364 --> 00:11:13,018
Oh.
You are not a corn crake.

351
00:11:13,062 --> 00:11:14,237
- But you heard the call?

352
00:11:14,280 --> 00:11:16,761
- Yes, it was... majestic.

353
00:11:16,804 --> 00:11:19,329
- Well, look what we caught
in our gill net,

354
00:11:19,372 --> 00:11:20,983
a couple of fresh, fatty trout.

355
00:11:21,026 --> 00:11:22,419
That'll last us
the next five days.

356
00:11:22,462 --> 00:11:24,029
More if we eat the egg sac.

357
00:11:24,073 --> 00:11:26,031
- Jake, the picnic.

358
00:11:26,075 --> 00:11:27,641
It attracted bees!

359
00:11:27,685 --> 00:11:29,382
- Ack.
Oh.

360
00:11:29,426 --> 00:11:31,036
Oh, God, they're everywhere!

361
00:11:31,080 --> 00:11:32,516
[screams]
Get away!

362
00:11:32,559 --> 00:11:33,604
Quick, everyone form a wall
around me!

363
00:11:33,647 --> 00:11:35,084
- Peralta.
- I'm sorry, Kevin.

364
00:11:35,127 --> 00:11:36,389
It's just I'm very allergic.

365
00:11:36,433 --> 00:11:37,608
If I get stung,
I have a terrible reaction.

366
00:11:37,651 --> 00:11:39,697
- Kind of like this?
- Oh, my—

367
00:11:39,740 --> 00:11:42,047
No, that's much worse,
I just get a scratchy throat.

368
00:11:42,091 --> 00:11:43,918
Why didn't you cower
behind someone?

369
00:11:47,270 --> 00:11:48,836
- All right, we should be good.

370
00:11:48,880 --> 00:11:49,881
I think the swarm is gone.

371
00:11:49,924 --> 00:11:50,795
- I think
I was only stung once.

372
00:11:50,838 --> 00:11:53,058
How do I look?

373
00:11:53,102 --> 00:11:54,538
- Good, good, very good.
- Normal, very normal.

374
00:11:54,581 --> 00:11:55,626
- Stop it.

375
00:11:55,669 --> 00:11:57,106
Kevin doesn't like to be
lied to.

376
00:11:57,149 --> 00:11:58,803
You're disgusting to look at.
- Thank you, Raymond.

377
00:11:58,846 --> 00:12:00,326
I have an EpiPen
back at the house.

378
00:12:00,370 --> 00:12:01,632
Would you call someone
to have them bring it?

379
00:12:01,675 --> 00:12:03,503
- There's no reception.
I'll just run back.

380
00:12:03,547 --> 00:12:05,157
I haven't done cardio
in 20 years.

381
00:12:05,201 --> 00:12:07,116
How hard can it be?

382
00:12:07,159 --> 00:12:09,205
It's immediately awful!

383
00:12:09,248 --> 00:12:11,511
- Here, while we wait,
you could try putting this

384
00:12:11,555 --> 00:12:12,947
chilled bottle of champagne
against your eyes.

385
00:12:12,991 --> 00:12:14,340
It might help.
- Peralta, why is there

386
00:12:14,384 --> 00:12:17,517
a romantic picnic sitting
in this remote clearing?

387
00:12:17,561 --> 00:12:19,954
You set this whole thing up,
didn't you?

388
00:12:19,998 --> 00:12:22,044
- Nuh-uh.
- You've manipulated us

389
00:12:22,087 --> 00:12:23,697
into spending time together.

390
00:12:23,741 --> 00:12:24,916
- Nuh-uh.

391
00:12:24,959 --> 00:12:25,830
- Is that your entire defense?
"Nuh-uh"?

392
00:12:25,873 --> 00:12:27,136
- Uh-huh.

393
00:12:27,179 --> 00:12:28,267
Okay, fine, all right?
Yes.

394
00:12:28,311 --> 00:12:30,095
But only because
I care about you.

395
00:12:30,139 --> 00:12:31,314
And by the way,
you should really make

396
00:12:31,357 --> 00:12:32,924
your shared calendar
less easy to access.

397
00:12:32,967 --> 00:12:34,578
- You got into our calendar?
- Yeah, you already knew that.

398
00:12:34,621 --> 00:12:35,970
You said I set
the whole thing up.

399
00:12:36,014 --> 00:12:36,928
- I was talking
about the picnic.

400
00:12:36,971 --> 00:12:38,277
What were you talking about?

401
00:12:38,321 --> 00:12:39,191
- Nuh-uh.

402
00:12:39,235 --> 00:12:40,497
- You tricked us into coming

403
00:12:40,540 --> 00:12:42,064
to the Lake House
at the same time.

404
00:12:42,107 --> 00:12:43,543
You did
a "Das Doppelte Lottchen."

405
00:12:43,587 --> 00:12:45,023
- What?
I don't know what that is.

406
00:12:45,067 --> 00:12:47,330
- "Das Doppelte Lottchen"!
- I'm only half.

407
00:12:47,373 --> 00:12:49,941
- It's a German novel
about a set of twins

408
00:12:49,984 --> 00:12:51,682
who try to reunite
their estranged parents.

409
00:12:51,725 --> 00:12:52,944
- That's the "Parent Trap"!

410
00:12:52,987 --> 00:12:54,815
I knew my stratagem
had classy origins.

411
00:12:54,859 --> 00:12:57,557
- Peralta,
this is my personal life.

412
00:12:57,601 --> 00:12:58,906
You've crossed a line.

413
00:12:58,950 --> 00:13:01,213
I'm leaving.
- So am I.

414
00:13:01,257 --> 00:13:03,476
- Oh, no, wait, Kevin—
- [grunts]

415
00:13:04,477 --> 00:13:06,784
- Are there tools in here?
You see a saw anywhere?

416
00:13:06,827 --> 00:13:08,090
- I told you to stay away,
Charles.

417
00:13:08,133 --> 00:13:09,439
I'm not into your energy.

418
00:13:09,482 --> 00:13:10,570
- Amy!

419
00:13:10,614 --> 00:13:12,442
Hi!
Hi, Amy!

420
00:13:12,485 --> 00:13:14,052
- Hi.

421
00:13:14,096 --> 00:13:15,619
Look, I just wanted to say
thank you

422
00:13:15,662 --> 00:13:17,229
for getting Mac to sleep.

423
00:13:17,273 --> 00:13:19,405
I was being really stubborn
earlier,

424
00:13:19,449 --> 00:13:22,147
and I guess
what I'm trying to say

425
00:13:22,191 --> 00:13:24,845
is can I please have
your nip tips?

426
00:13:24,889 --> 00:13:27,239
- You don't want my nip tips,
those crusty old things.

427
00:13:27,283 --> 00:13:28,588
- Oh, God,
I can't be here for this.

428
00:13:28,632 --> 00:13:30,634
Oh, my mouth is so dry.
It's all bad.

429
00:13:30,677 --> 00:13:32,984
- What's all bad?
- I can't tell you, Amy.

430
00:13:33,027 --> 00:13:34,028
- What can't you tell me?

431
00:13:34,072 --> 00:13:37,728
- It's too real.
I need to leave.

432
00:13:37,771 --> 00:13:39,730
Damn it, I was looking
for somewhere to be alone.

433
00:13:39,773 --> 00:13:41,297
- Sorry, I came out here
looking for a signal

434
00:13:41,340 --> 00:13:42,994
to call Hitchcock, but no luck.

435
00:13:43,037 --> 00:13:44,648
I can take my chips and go.

436
00:13:44,691 --> 00:13:47,041
- Wait, you have chips?

437
00:13:47,085 --> 00:13:48,782
You could stay.
- Oh.

438
00:13:48,826 --> 00:13:51,263
- So we got off to a bad start
there with the bees

439
00:13:51,307 --> 00:13:53,265
and Kevin rolling down
the hill,

440
00:13:53,309 --> 00:13:54,875
and then, of course,
the second swarm of bees,

441
00:13:54,919 --> 00:13:56,790
but we're good now, right?

442
00:13:56,834 --> 00:13:58,401
Can you guys hear me?

443
00:13:58,444 --> 00:14:00,272
You keep moving away from me
for some reason.

444
00:14:00,316 --> 00:14:02,883
- Ugh, I wish a bee would sting
me in both ears right now

445
00:14:02,927 --> 00:14:04,146
so they'd seal shut as well.

446
00:14:04,189 --> 00:14:05,321
- What was that?
I couldn't hear you!

447
00:14:05,364 --> 00:14:06,713
I'll just assume you said,
"Keep going."

448
00:14:06,757 --> 00:14:08,498
Anyways, yeah, I just figured

449
00:14:08,541 --> 00:14:09,890
if I could
get you guys together,

450
00:14:09,934 --> 00:14:11,327
I could create
a magical moment.

451
00:14:11,370 --> 00:14:14,373
But of course, we now know
that magic doesn't exist.

452
00:14:14,417 --> 00:14:15,592
- Shh!

453
00:14:15,635 --> 00:14:16,506
It's a corn crake.

454
00:14:16,549 --> 00:14:18,638
- Oh, no, I can't believe it.

455
00:14:18,682 --> 00:14:21,206
I finally spot a corn crake,
and my eyes are swollen shut.

456
00:14:21,250 --> 00:14:22,947
- It's okay, Kevin.
I'll describe it to you.

457
00:14:22,990 --> 00:14:24,557
Okay, have you ever seen
a duck?

458
00:14:24,601 --> 00:14:26,298
- Peralta, I got this.
- Oh, okay.

459
00:14:26,342 --> 00:14:29,823
- The beak color
is Pantone 4685C.

460
00:14:29,867 --> 00:14:31,260
- Mm.

461
00:14:31,303 --> 00:14:36,003
— The wing is Pantone 2322
- C
spotted with 4515C.

462
00:14:36,047 --> 00:14:37,396
- Ooh.

463
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:42,184
— The tail is Pantone 7525
- C
with bands of 419C.

464
00:14:42,227 --> 00:14:43,315
- Oh, my, my.

465
00:14:43,359 --> 00:14:45,622
- Oh, Kevin, the throat...

466
00:14:45,665 --> 00:14:49,713
Pantone 7528C.

467
00:14:49,756 --> 00:14:51,497
- Oh, Raymond.

468
00:14:51,541 --> 00:14:53,934
- Those are some hot Pantones.

469
00:14:53,978 --> 00:14:56,328
- Okay, Barbecue.
- Mm-hmm.

470
00:14:56,372 --> 00:14:57,982
- Sweet Maui Onion,

471
00:14:58,025 --> 00:15:00,332
and the surprising underdog,
Original.

472
00:15:00,376 --> 00:15:02,029
- I think I'm ready to crown
a Chipeon.

473
00:15:02,073 --> 00:15:03,292
- Chipeon?
That's good.

474
00:15:03,335 --> 00:15:05,119
- Yeah, I came up with it
because I misspoke.

475
00:15:05,163 --> 00:15:08,297
- [laughing]

476
00:15:09,733 --> 00:15:11,343
- [laughs]

477
00:15:11,387 --> 00:15:12,997
[sighs] Can I join you?

478
00:15:13,040 --> 00:15:14,259
Mac's never been asleep
this long,

479
00:15:14,303 --> 00:15:15,521
and I don't know
what to do with myself.

480
00:15:15,565 --> 00:15:16,566
- Charles locked your kid
in the room.

481
00:15:16,609 --> 00:15:18,045
- What?
- You made me say it.

482
00:15:18,089 --> 00:15:19,438
If I didn't, you would've
stayed here and ruined this

483
00:15:19,482 --> 00:15:21,048
good thing I got going
with Scully and his chips.

484
00:15:21,092 --> 00:15:22,746
- Wait, Mac is locked
in a room?

485
00:15:22,789 --> 00:15:25,227
Oh, my...

486
00:15:25,270 --> 00:15:26,358
Charles!
- Amy!

487
00:15:26,402 --> 00:15:27,446
I was just doing
a little handiwork,

488
00:15:27,490 --> 00:15:28,708
you know,
fixing up the old house.

489
00:15:28,752 --> 00:15:30,101
- I know you locked my son
in there.

490
00:15:30,144 --> 00:15:31,842
- I'm sorry.
I tried everything.

491
00:15:31,885 --> 00:15:33,757
Maybe he'll be happy
growing up in that room.

492
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:34,975
- Oh, shut up, Charles!

493
00:15:35,019 --> 00:15:36,368
I'll get him out.
Move.

494
00:15:36,412 --> 00:15:37,891
- I'm telling you,
it's impossible.

495
00:15:37,935 --> 00:15:39,197
- Not for his mother.

496
00:15:39,241 --> 00:15:41,634
[screams, grunts]

497
00:15:41,678 --> 00:15:45,159
[baby crying]

498
00:15:45,203 --> 00:15:46,552
- Wow!

499
00:15:46,596 --> 00:15:48,162
- Sorry that took me so long.

500
00:15:48,206 --> 00:15:49,816
I cramped up halfway and then
crawled for a little while.

501
00:15:49,860 --> 00:15:51,427
Maybe I should think
about slimming down.

502
00:15:51,470 --> 00:15:52,645
- No, it's actually good
you didn't make it back.

503
00:15:52,689 --> 00:15:54,430
- Oh, thank you
for saying that.

504
00:15:54,473 --> 00:15:56,258
Look, I can't change my body,
it defines me.

505
00:15:56,301 --> 00:15:57,998
- No, no, no,
we really saw a corn crake.

506
00:15:58,042 --> 00:15:59,522
Holt had to describe it
to Kevin,

507
00:15:59,565 --> 00:16:01,045
and now he's leading him,
by the hand, out of the woods.

508
00:16:01,088 --> 00:16:03,265
The Parent Trap worked!
I can't wait to tell the squad.

509
00:16:03,308 --> 00:16:04,788
- Wait, wait, let me give Kevin
the EpiPen,

510
00:16:04,831 --> 00:16:06,355
and then we can
tell them together.

511
00:16:06,398 --> 00:16:09,183
- Okay, whoa, whoa.
Pump the brakes there, Sonic.

512
00:16:09,227 --> 00:16:11,055
- What?
- Sonic the Hedgehog.

513
00:16:11,098 --> 00:16:13,318
You've been hogging that hedge
while I was out on a ledge.

514
00:16:13,362 --> 00:16:14,754
No, you didn't have
to deal with anyone

515
00:16:14,798 --> 00:16:15,799
saying it was a bad idea,

516
00:16:15,842 --> 00:16:16,930
so you don't get
the credit either.

517
00:16:16,974 --> 00:16:20,151
This was 100% all me,
Dr. Robotnik.

518
00:16:20,194 --> 00:16:21,761
- Who?
- Sonic's archnemesis!

519
00:16:21,805 --> 00:16:23,763
You never played a video game
or watched a movie, Terry?

520
00:16:23,807 --> 00:16:25,287
Get a life, dude!

521
00:16:25,330 --> 00:16:27,289
They were being
so sweet with each other

522
00:16:27,332 --> 00:16:28,899
and holding hands,
it was amazing.

523
00:16:28,942 --> 00:16:30,335
They're totally back in love.

524
00:16:30,379 --> 00:16:32,206
- Peralta,
I need to ask you something.

525
00:16:32,250 --> 00:16:33,860
- Let me guess.
Will I be the best man

526
00:16:33,904 --> 00:16:36,646
at a last-minute vow renewal
ceremony that will serve

527
00:16:36,689 --> 00:16:38,648
as an emotional capper
to this magical weekend?

528
00:16:38,691 --> 00:16:40,214
- No, I need you
to move your car.

529
00:16:40,258 --> 00:16:42,608
Kevin has decided
to leave immediately.

530
00:16:42,652 --> 00:16:44,958
- Kevin Cozner
leaving the Lake House.

531
00:16:45,002 --> 00:16:47,091
[light music]

532
00:16:47,134 --> 00:16:48,962
♪

533
00:16:49,006 --> 00:16:51,617
- This was 100% all Jake.

534
00:16:51,661 --> 00:16:53,315
- Oh, Terry.

535
00:16:55,969 --> 00:16:58,189
- Amy, will you please pass
the mini crab cakes?

536
00:16:58,232 --> 00:16:59,364
- Are you sure
you can be trusted

537
00:16:59,408 --> 00:17:01,235
with something so small
and delicate?

538
00:17:01,279 --> 00:17:03,063
- I can tell you're upset,
but you should know

539
00:17:03,107 --> 00:17:05,718
that I was locked in a room
for 16 days as a child,

540
00:17:05,762 --> 00:17:07,111
and I turned out just fine.

541
00:17:07,154 --> 00:17:09,026
- No, you didn't.
You're a freak!

542
00:17:09,069 --> 00:17:10,810
- Okay, I'm staying out
of this one.

543
00:17:10,854 --> 00:17:12,551
- Shocking—I didn't realize
you were capable

544
00:17:12,595 --> 00:17:13,857
of staying out of anything.

545
00:17:13,900 --> 00:17:15,249
- We have an announcement.

546
00:17:15,293 --> 00:17:17,077
We're here to crown the winner
of this year's

547
00:17:17,121 --> 00:17:19,210
Great Tournament of Chips.
Rosa?

548
00:17:19,253 --> 00:17:21,952
- The Chipeon is...
Smoky Bacon Chicken.

549
00:17:21,995 --> 00:17:23,693
- She's so high.
- Yeah.

550
00:17:23,736 --> 00:17:25,216
Sounds pretty good, though.

551
00:17:25,259 --> 00:17:27,610
- Ugh, you guys are duds.
Scully and I are gonna bounce.

552
00:17:29,307 --> 00:17:31,396
- Oh, sir,
that's a dribble cup.

553
00:17:31,440 --> 00:17:32,658
You're dripping on yourself.

554
00:17:32,702 --> 00:17:34,268
- Am I?

555
00:17:34,312 --> 00:17:36,923
- Okay.
Look, I'm really sorry.

556
00:17:36,967 --> 00:17:38,229
- No need to apologize.

557
00:17:38,272 --> 00:17:39,970
Your Das Doppelte Lottchen
scheme worked.

558
00:17:40,013 --> 00:17:42,973
You manufactured
a perfect romantic moment,

559
00:17:43,016 --> 00:17:45,628
and I allowed myself to
imagine, as Kevin held my hand,

560
00:17:45,671 --> 00:17:47,238
that he still felt something
for me.

561
00:17:47,281 --> 00:17:49,588
When we came back,
I walked him to his room,

562
00:17:49,632 --> 00:17:53,549
and just as I was working up
the courage to ask him to stay,

563
00:17:53,592 --> 00:17:55,812
he said

564
00:17:55,855 --> 00:17:57,944
we shouldn't spend
any more time together.

565
00:17:57,988 --> 00:18:01,644
Well, at least now I know
that my marriage is over.

566
00:18:02,949 --> 00:18:06,997
So thank you, Peralta.

567
00:18:08,085 --> 00:18:11,175
Raymond Holt
leaving the living room.

568
00:18:11,218 --> 00:18:14,091
[light music]

569
00:18:14,134 --> 00:18:16,528
- Hey, crazy what a good mood
Mac is in.

570
00:18:16,572 --> 00:18:17,703
- You mean given the fact that

571
00:18:17,747 --> 00:18:19,444
he was locked in a prison
by Charles?

572
00:18:19,488 --> 00:18:20,750
- How long did he sleep?

573
00:18:20,793 --> 00:18:22,099
- You mean before he was
rescued from the prison

574
00:18:22,142 --> 00:18:23,448
he was locked in by Charles?

575
00:18:23,492 --> 00:18:24,623
- I guess.

576
00:18:24,667 --> 00:18:25,798
- Three hours.

577
00:18:25,842 --> 00:18:27,452
- Whoa.
What did Charles do?

578
00:18:27,496 --> 00:18:29,367
- You mean besides...
both: Locking him in a prison.

579
00:18:29,411 --> 00:18:30,499
- Got it.
I'll stop asking.

580
00:18:30,542 --> 00:18:31,978
Well, whatever he did,

581
00:18:32,022 --> 00:18:33,458
I'm loving his mood.
- Whatever.

582
00:18:33,502 --> 00:18:35,460
- I still can't believe
my scheme didn't work.

583
00:18:35,504 --> 00:18:37,549
I mean, we saw a corn crake
and everything.

584
00:18:37,593 --> 00:18:38,942
- I know.
What are the odds?

585
00:18:38,985 --> 00:18:40,247
- Right?
I have to say,

586
00:18:40,291 --> 00:18:41,858
I don't see what the big deal
is all about.

587
00:18:41,901 --> 00:18:43,381
This is what they
actually look like.

588
00:18:43,425 --> 00:18:45,644
- Oh, that is not
an attractive bird.

589
00:18:45,688 --> 00:18:48,125
- I know!
It's like a dumb duck!

590
00:18:48,168 --> 00:18:49,779
And this is what its call
sounds like.

591
00:18:49,822 --> 00:18:51,128
[bird calling]

592
00:18:51,171 --> 00:18:54,523
- Oh, it's horrible!
It sounds like a Taser.

593
00:18:54,566 --> 00:18:56,829
- No.
It's wonderful.

594
00:18:56,873 --> 00:18:59,179
I have to go!

595
00:18:59,223 --> 00:19:00,616
Sir?

596
00:19:00,659 --> 00:19:02,356
- What are you doing here,
Peralta?

597
00:19:02,400 --> 00:19:04,097
- I wanna prove to you
that you're wrong to think

598
00:19:04,141 --> 00:19:05,664
that Kevin doesn't have
feelings for you anymore.

599
00:19:05,708 --> 00:19:07,449
- Okay.
What is he doing here?

600
00:19:07,492 --> 00:19:09,102
- Oh, I wanna prove to him

601
00:19:09,146 --> 00:19:10,669
that he was wrong
for hedging all day.

602
00:19:10,713 --> 00:19:12,236
But that's our own separate
thing, so you can ignore it.

603
00:19:12,279 --> 00:19:14,499
Sir, listen.
I think Kevin wanted to stay.

604
00:19:14,543 --> 00:19:15,674
The only reason he left

605
00:19:15,718 --> 00:19:17,328
is 'cause he didn't know
how you felt.

606
00:19:17,371 --> 00:19:19,156
- Why would you think that?
He's made no effort whatsoever.

607
00:19:19,199 --> 00:19:20,897
- Or has he?
Did you know that

608
00:19:20,940 --> 00:19:22,420
Kevin is better at bird calls
than you?

609
00:19:22,464 --> 00:19:25,467
- Oh, a strange,
hurtful non sequitur.

610
00:19:25,510 --> 00:19:26,990
- Now, who made
the first corn crake call?

611
00:19:27,033 --> 00:19:28,295
- I believe I did.
- Correct.

612
00:19:28,339 --> 00:19:29,862
Kevin and I heard you,
and he responded.

613
00:19:29,906 --> 00:19:32,038
But get this, sir.
You made the wrong call.

614
00:19:32,082 --> 00:19:34,301
This is what a rooting
corn crake sounds like.

615
00:19:34,345 --> 00:19:36,129
[bird calling]

616
00:19:36,173 --> 00:19:38,349
- The call you made
was for a scarlet warbler.

617
00:19:38,392 --> 00:19:40,917
A trash bird.
- Okay, so you made your point.

618
00:19:40,960 --> 00:19:42,875
I'm a trash man
who only knows trash birds.

619
00:19:42,919 --> 00:19:44,486
- No, that is not my point.

620
00:19:44,529 --> 00:19:46,705
My point is, Kevin knew
it wasn't a corn crake,

621
00:19:46,749 --> 00:19:48,446
but he went to it anyway.

622
00:19:48,490 --> 00:19:51,057
- Because he was going to you,
not the bird!

623
00:19:51,101 --> 00:19:53,625
He still loves you!
Our plan worked!

624
00:19:53,669 --> 00:19:55,061
- Our plan?
- Yeah!

625
00:19:55,105 --> 00:19:57,847
Terry is off the hedge
and on the ledge!

626
00:19:57,890 --> 00:19:59,544
- Well, that means a lot,
coming from you Jeffords,

627
00:19:59,588 --> 00:20:00,980
given how much you hate ledges.

628
00:20:01,024 --> 00:20:02,939
- People don't know about Terry
hating ledges!

629
00:20:02,982 --> 00:20:04,897
This is new!

630
00:20:04,941 --> 00:20:08,248
- Hey, Amy,
I wanted to give you this.

631
00:20:08,292 --> 00:20:10,250
I made Mac
a truffle squash puree.

632
00:20:10,294 --> 00:20:11,817
I'm not trying to show you
how to do anything,

633
00:20:11,861 --> 00:20:13,471
I'm just trying to apologize.

634
00:20:13,515 --> 00:20:15,255
- It's okay, Charles.

635
00:20:15,299 --> 00:20:18,432
I actually learned something
from you yesterday.

636
00:20:18,476 --> 00:20:20,696
Mac has trouble sleeping
because I bother him too much.

637
00:20:20,739 --> 00:20:23,220
When he was locked in that room
no one could check on him,

638
00:20:23,263 --> 00:20:26,092
and it was the longest nap
he's ever taken.

639
00:20:26,136 --> 00:20:28,225
So thank you for the mousse.

640
00:20:28,268 --> 00:20:29,574
- I can't believe
you actually took it.

641
00:20:29,618 --> 00:20:30,836
- Of course I took it.

642
00:20:30,880 --> 00:20:32,882
You locked my baby
in a room, Charles.

643
00:20:32,925 --> 00:20:34,927
You're gonna be cooking for him
until he goes to college, okay?

644
00:20:34,971 --> 00:20:36,538
- Okay.
- Great, thanks.

645
00:20:36,581 --> 00:20:38,452
- How's it going, sir?
You look chipper.

646
00:20:38,496 --> 00:20:40,716
- Yes, well,
I called Kevin and told him

647
00:20:40,759 --> 00:20:43,240
I still have feelings for him,
and he said he felt the same.

648
00:20:43,283 --> 00:20:46,896
So we begin
couples counseling next week.

649
00:20:46,939 --> 00:20:50,508
- That's great, sir.
I'm so glad.

650
00:20:50,552 --> 00:20:53,946
Looks like Captain Holt caught
a fatty trout in his gill net.

651
00:20:53,990 --> 00:20:56,122
- You watched "Alone"?
- Every single episode.

652
00:20:56,166 --> 00:20:57,994
Terry has not slept!

653
00:20:58,037 --> 00:20:59,865
- Hey, Rosa, you wanna take
a couple days off,

654
00:20:59,909 --> 00:21:01,606
drive to Buffalo,
see the warehouse

655
00:21:01,650 --> 00:21:04,087
where Sweet Maui Onion chips
are imported to?

656
00:21:04,130 --> 00:21:05,305
Unless you don't wanna hang out

657
00:21:05,349 --> 00:21:07,307
'cause you're not
stoned anymore.

658
00:21:07,351 --> 00:21:08,482
- Actually, Buffalo sounds
kind of cool.

659
00:21:08,526 --> 00:21:09,527
- Seriously?

660
00:21:09,571 --> 00:21:10,702
That's just not
the weed talking?

661
00:21:10,746 --> 00:21:11,877
- Oh, no, I'm not high
at all anymore.

662
00:21:11,921 --> 00:21:13,357
Oh, no, I was so high.

663
00:21:13,400 --> 00:21:15,011
- Good news.
While you were asleep,

664
00:21:15,054 --> 00:21:16,708
we finally got cell reception.

665
00:21:16,752 --> 00:21:18,101
- What's up, cucks?

666
00:21:18,144 --> 00:21:20,451
So how did everybody lose
their V-card?

667
00:21:20,494 --> 00:21:21,408
I'll go first.

668
00:21:21,452 --> 00:21:22,975
- Amy was right.
Drugs are bad.

669
00:21:23,019 --> 00:21:25,021
- Fremulon.

670
00:21:25,064 --> 00:21:27,153
- Not a doctor.
Shh.

